  "prompt": "How fast can helicopters travel?",
  "response": "The speed of helicopters can vary significantly depending on the type and design. Generally, most helicopters have a cruising speed between 100 to 160 knots (about 115 to 185 miles per hour or 185 to 300 kilometers per hour). \n\nSome specific examples include:\n\n- **Light helicopters** (like the Robinson R44): They typically cruise around 110 knots (127 mph or 204 km/h).\n- **Medium helicopters** (such as the Bell 206): They often have a cruising speed around 120-140 knots (138-161 mph or 222-259 km/h).\n- **Heavy and high-performance helicopters** (like the Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk): These can cruise at speeds up to about 150-160 knots (173-185 mph or 278-300 km/h).\n- The fastest military helicopters, like the Eurocopter X3, have achieved speeds of over 250 knots (about 287 mph or 462 km/h) in experimental tests.\n\nThe speed can be affected by various factors, including weight, altitude, and weather conditions, as well as the helicopter's design and intended purpose.",
